{"questionId":"19896","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Dana has collected some data regarding the heights <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> (metres) of waves against a pier at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn></math> randomly chosen times in a single day. This data is shown in the table below.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/9ec7e13106ac7d248e4a3acfa98cd2a86e4e4002.png\"></p>\n<p>She wishes to perform a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>-test at the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>%</mo></math> significance level to see if the height of waves&nbsp;could be modelled by a normal distribution. Her null hypothesis is</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left:30px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>H</mtext><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></math> The data can be modelled by a normal distribution.</p>\n<p>From the table she calculates the mean of the heights in her sample to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>828</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math> and the&nbsp;standard deviation of the heights <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math> to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>257</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>She calculates the expected values for each interval under this null hypothesis, and some&nbsp;of these values are shown in the table below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/2652358763dd5e151599b1cdf934c24e42c7d2a8.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>&nbsp;and the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>, giving your answers correct to one decimal&nbsp;place.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Using&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>x</mi><mo>¯</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>828</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>s</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>260</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>(M1)</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>A</strong><strong>1A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[3 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19896","referenceCode":"EXN.2.AHL.TZ0.3b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the value of a and the value of b, giving your answers correct to one decimal place.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.9—Normal distribution and calculations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}